WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.360
All right, so let me start by motivating iPyShiny with this interactive web application.

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:19.680
So in Core.Shiny itself, you know, we have the ability to only render like a few different

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:27.920
things like images and plots and text, like some very basic sort of core utilities for

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:29.920
rendering Python objects.

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:35.119
Let me mention this is also very experimental at this point, and partially the reason why

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:41.560
it's in a separate package at this point is we've been experimenting with the ability

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:46.000
to render iPyWidgets with Shiny.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:53.759
So if you're not already familiar with iPyWidgets, it kind of provides this foundation for Python

00:00:53.759 --> 00:01:03.480
developers to like create a Python package that wraps a JavaScript library, like a library

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:10.839
like Leaflet for creating interactive maps and provide an interface in Python that people

00:01:10.839 --> 00:01:20.959
can then use that Python package to create these interactive data visualizations inside

00:01:20.959 --> 00:01:21.959
of Jupyter.

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:29.239
So traditionally, the main sort of platform for using iPyWidgets is Jupyter, but we've

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:38.120
kind of provided this kind of wrapper to allow you to write the same iPyWidgets code and

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:46.400
just kind of get that into Shiny in the way that makes the most sense to.

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:52.279
So this is kind of a motivating example where I have some data here.

00:01:52.279 --> 00:02:01.959
This is showing a super zip score, and these super zip scores are really like some combination

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:13.479
of percent college educated, median income, and I think population for each zip code in

00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:15.080
the US.

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:21.399
So you can go to this dropdown and instead of like looking at some combination of income

00:02:21.399 --> 00:02:24.440
and education, essentially, you can look at just education.

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:33.759
So you can see compared to this overall score, percent college educated is a lot more highly

00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:38.199
dense than the Northeast in the US.

00:02:38.199 --> 00:02:44.520
And then you can see median income is actually maybe more highly correlated with this overall

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:46.160
score.

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:48.520
It's at least more widespread out.

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:53.679
Basically three different main measures that we're looking at here.

00:02:53.679 --> 00:03:02.759
And then this is a density plot of the overall score for all of the US, essentially.

00:03:02.759 --> 00:03:07.919
So you can see this overall score, there's a pretty high concentration, you know, around

00:03:07.919 --> 00:03:10.720
zero to 20.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:17.720
And you know, same similar for college, but it's more pronounced and pretty same similar

00:03:17.720 --> 00:03:20.160
distribution for income.

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:25.160
And then this is the log of the population.

00:03:25.160 --> 00:03:29.880
Just if I didn't take the log here, it'd be super, you know, you basically just see a

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:35.440
straight line up here, and then a very long tail.

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:40.320
And the point of having these density plots here is this is programmed in such a way that

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:43.520
I can zoom in on this application.

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:49.440
And these density plots will update whenever I change the bounding box of this map, I will

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:57.479
recompute the density of these things conditional on just the zip codes within this area.

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:06.559
So as I zoom in here to like the DC area, you can see like the inbounds density here,

00:04:06.559 --> 00:04:14.880
there's a much higher density of very high overall scores in the DC area.

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:21.720
And that's really a combination of the college percent college educated and the income both

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:27.679
being, you know, much higher in these areas, as well as a higher population, I guess, population

00:04:27.679 --> 00:04:29.160
density, I should say.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:35.519
And then if you want to get more detailed into like, what specifically is in this view,

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:39.279
there's kind of this details tab over here.

00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:45.760
That tells me there's 123 zip codes currently in that bounding box.

00:04:45.799 --> 00:04:54.440
And amongst those 123 zips, 23% are considered super zips, which just means their score is

00:04:54.440 --> 00:05:00.279
like above a certain threshold, and their mean income is nearly 100,000.

00:05:00.279 --> 00:05:04.679
The mean population is a little over 10,000.

00:05:04.679 --> 00:05:08.279
And the mean college educated is nearly 40%.

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:15.559
And then if I wanted, like if I had other data about these zip codes, you know, I can

00:05:15.559 --> 00:05:21.640
see other information here, like their relative rank amongst all of the zip codes and stuff

00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:23.559
like that.

00:05:23.559 --> 00:05:29.480
And this is also hooked up to another map where if I want to click on a particular county

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:37.920
and see exactly where that county is, I can zoom in on this map.

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:44.279
And I can see, you know, where this, sorry, zip code is actually located.

00:05:44.279 --> 00:05:49.079
And this is currently a bug when I click on this pop up, the table goes away, but hopefully

00:05:49.079 --> 00:05:54.359
that will get fixed sometime soon, where, you know, I could click on this marker as

00:05:54.359 --> 00:05:58.720
well to see basically that same information displayed again.

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:03.559
So the repo's name is IPyShiny.

00:06:03.559 --> 00:06:09.600
If you go to the GitHub page, it will have some information on how to install it and

00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.359
a quick overview on how to use it.

00:06:12.359 --> 00:06:20.119
There's a couple different ways you can actually render an IPyWidget with IPyShiny.

00:06:20.119 --> 00:06:27.480
And the first use that it goes over is, should feel really intuitive if you are already an

00:06:27.519 --> 00:06:33.320
IPyWidget user instead of like a Shiny user.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:40.320
So hopefully most of the audience is in that former group where, you know, you want to,

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:44.679
like always with any Shiny app, create your user interface.

00:06:44.679 --> 00:06:53.119
And in that user interface, use this output widget, which comes from IPyShiny.

00:06:53.119 --> 00:06:59.279
And like any other sort of UI component, you want to give it an ID that you'll then

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:03.200
reference on the server.

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:08.920
And inside of the server function, the kind of recommended way to do this is to first

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:19.040
initialize the widget object when the server function first executes.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:20.920
So this will only run once.

00:07:21.239 --> 00:07:30.359
We'll be initializing the map just once with a center location and a zoom level.

00:07:30.359 --> 00:07:36.920
And then once you're ready, you want to call register widget with the ID that should match

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:43.600
this ID on the user interface to basically say, I have my widget object here that I want

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:49.279
you to perform like an initial draw of for the application.

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:55.760
And then for all of the other updates, you're actually performing side effects.

00:07:55.760 --> 00:07:59.920
You're not like redrawn or like recreating the widget from scratch.

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:04.399
You're essentially just mutating properties on that widget.

00:08:04.399 --> 00:08:11.959
So it's a little bit different if you're coming from a Shiny world where we essentially re-initialize

00:08:11.959 --> 00:08:18.279
and redraw a widget every time we want to update it using our code.

00:08:18.279 --> 00:08:23.399
But here we will register essentially side effects.

00:08:23.399 --> 00:08:28.799
So we haven't seen this yet from Shiny, but this is a decorator that comes from the Shiny

00:08:28.799 --> 00:08:32.440
reactive sub package.

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:39.119
So we saw reactive calc before where this is a calc, you might remember, wants you to

00:08:39.119 --> 00:08:40.780
return a value.

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:48.239
So it reads some other reactive values and then returns a reactive value.

00:08:48.239 --> 00:08:54.599
But with side effects, this also can read reactive values, but you're not going to be

00:08:54.599 --> 00:08:58.099
calling this function for a return value.

00:08:58.099 --> 00:09:02.659
You're going to be calling this function for its side effects.

00:09:02.659 --> 00:09:09.479
So when I say reactive effect, I don't really need to give this a name because Shiny isn't

00:09:09.479 --> 00:09:11.659
going to like put this anywhere.

00:09:11.659 --> 00:09:15.940
So I can just use this underscore and define a function.

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:24.520
And then I will read the zoom input value, which is coming from our Shiny input slider

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:27.440
up here at the zoom.

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:32.099
And that is going to then...

00:09:32.099 --> 00:09:39.619
What this is essentially saying is whenever the slider changes, update the maps zoom attribute.

00:09:39.619 --> 00:09:48.179
So map.zoom is like an IPyWidget property that will be mutating every time the value

00:09:48.179 --> 00:09:50.320
of this zoom input value changes.

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:51.320
All right.

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:57.880
So we just went over like the side effect that allows me to change this input slider

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:02.840
to change the zoom level on the map.

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:09.099
But what if I wanted to go the other way in the sense of, you know, I can also use

00:10:09.099 --> 00:10:16.039
this control that's directly attached to the widget instance on the IPyWidget.

00:10:16.039 --> 00:10:21.039
If I wanted to zoom in this way, what if I wanted to essentially have that bidirectional

00:10:21.039 --> 00:10:29.039
communication of changing the zoom on the map, update the slider as well.

00:10:29.039 --> 00:10:34.000
So in order to do something like this, where you're kind of treating the IPyWidget like

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:43.799
an input control to then update some other thing on your user interface, then you want

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:54.979
to use this helper function that again comes from IPyShiny to this reactive read essentially

00:10:54.979 --> 00:11:01.780
allows me to read this zoom property on the map object in the same way that I would read

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:06.539
like in a true shiny input value like this input.zoom.

00:11:06.539 --> 00:11:12.059
By using this reactive read here inside of this reactive side effect, that will ensure

00:11:12.059 --> 00:11:17.739
whenever the zoom property changes on this map, this function is going to re-execute

00:11:17.739 --> 00:11:22.039
and perform side effects.

00:11:22.039 --> 00:11:30.099
So I'll get the zoom level from the map here and use that to inform this function that's

00:11:30.099 --> 00:11:33.679
coming from shiny to update the slider.

00:11:33.679 --> 00:11:40.520
So this is coming from the UI sub package to say, update this slider with an ID of zoom

00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:45.580
and update its value to whatever the zoom level is on the map, right?

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:49.580
So this is like, you know, changes from the slider to the map.

00:11:49.580 --> 00:11:53.059
And if you want to go the other way from the map to the slider, you could do something

00:11:53.059 --> 00:11:56.760
like this.

00:11:56.760 --> 00:12:06.080
And then this last part here is basically to get this text up here showing the current

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:12.539
latitude and longitude on the bounding box of this map, which will change whenever this

00:12:12.539 --> 00:12:18.679
zoom level changes, but I can also pan on the map to get, you know, a different bounding

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:21.500
box with different latitude and longitude.

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:28.900
If I wanted to do something like this, this is available on the maps bounds attribute.

00:12:28.900 --> 00:12:34.859
So normally if you wanted to read this property in like a Jupyter context, you would just

00:12:34.859 --> 00:12:41.000
type out map dot or map dot bounds, and then enter on your console and that would give

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.659
you the current bounds.

00:12:43.659 --> 00:12:46.700
But we want to reactively read this.

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:55.760
Whenever the bounds change, we want this output to get invalidated and basically re-execute.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:59.380
So that's why we use the reactive read here.

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:07.159
And then from this bounds, I'm just getting the latitude and longitude in a more usable

00:13:07.159 --> 00:13:08.559
way.

00:13:08.559 --> 00:13:13.159
And then returning a string with the current latitude and longitude and rendering that

00:13:13.159 --> 00:13:14.159
as text.

00:13:14.159 --> 00:13:22.099
Yeah, that basically kind of covers the core of what you would need to do something like,

00:13:22.099 --> 00:13:26.919
you know, coordinate other controls with a widget in terms of like keeping its state

00:13:26.919 --> 00:13:29.960
in sync with other things in your application.

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:37.400
And also keep in mind that like if you are coming from like an R shiny world and this

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:41.520
doesn't make a whole lot of sense to you, or it's like, you know, kind of a foreign

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:47.760
programming paradigm that you're not so keen on using.

00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:57.159
We do also in IPyShiny provide like a more render text like interface.

00:13:57.159 --> 00:14:00.719
You can initialize widgets inside of a reactive context.

00:14:00.719 --> 00:14:07.840
So there might be situations where you really do want the, you know, some parameter that

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:14.919
goes into initializing a widget to come from a reactive value before we just kind of like

00:14:14.919 --> 00:14:18.159
had a hard coded value of four.

00:14:18.159 --> 00:14:23.599
But if you just needed like, you know, your slider to redraw the map, for instance, every

00:14:23.599 --> 00:14:29.919
time you change the slider, you could do something like this, which would reinitialize and redraw

00:14:29.919 --> 00:14:40.760
from scratch that map object, which if that redrawing is relatively cheap, that can be

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:45.919
a totally fine way to approach how to render widgets with Shiny.

00:14:45.919 --> 00:14:52.000
And again, this is going to feel like a little bit more natural in some cases for Shiny users.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:57.760
Because you're not having to deal with side effects and we generally kind of recommend

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:03.799
avoiding side effects as much as possible because it can make your application logic harder to reason about.

00:15:03.799 --> 00:15:10.400
Yeah, this other option is available to you, but to really highlight the situation where you do

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:19.440
really want the side effects is maybe an example like this, where I'm using Plotly to render a

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:23.640
scatterplot with, say, 10,000 or maybe more points.

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:25.760
Don't worry too much about like this code.

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:36.200
This code is just like fitting a linear regression to like 10,000 different random X and Y coordinates.

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:46.599
And then I'm going to create a scatterplot down here using Plotly.

00:15:46.599 --> 00:15:58.760
But really the key part here is, you know, I'm using this register widget way of like basically doing all of the work

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:01.400
ahead of time to say, here's my scatterplot.

00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:04.159
I know that this thing isn't going to need to be redrawn.

00:16:04.159 --> 00:16:10.159
So I'm going to initialize with the scatterplot, register it to do that initial draw.

00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:19.400
And then I will basically register the side effect to happen whenever I click this show fit button here,

00:16:19.400 --> 00:16:21.840
which is tied to this checkbox.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:34.599
Then I just want to basically toggle the visibility of this fitted line that I've added here inside of the figure widget object.

00:16:34.599 --> 00:16:37.840
Right. So the scatterplot is actually two different pieces.

00:16:37.840 --> 00:16:42.840
One, the actual markers, like the black dots here for the scatterplot.

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:51.359
But then I've also layered on a fitted line that thankfully with like the way Plotly is set up,

00:16:51.359 --> 00:17:00.320
you can then mutate like the visibility of that specific line trace is what Plotly would call this.

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:12.040
So if you tried to do something like this, where instead imagine you were creating this figure widget object inside of a render widget context,

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:22.359
every time you, every time the show fit value changed, you would have to re-initialize and redraw, you know,

00:17:22.359 --> 00:17:29.000
a ton of different points and you would get like a bit of lag because every time you click,

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:30.760
it has to redo all of that work.

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:35.719
So, yeah, it's kind of a line that people will have to walk in the sense of like,

00:17:35.719 --> 00:17:42.680
this is really easy and quick to get started with something displaying inside of Shiny.

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:51.640
But if you're in a situation where you really need performant updates, other outputs don't depend on your widget state.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:58.319
And it's really convenient to initialize like this is a handy way to go.

00:17:58.319 --> 00:18:03.719
But in the case where you need performance, this is this is going to be really useful.

00:18:03.719 --> 00:18:04.160
So.

